  "text": "Likewise, exposure to health hazards, independently of individual behaviour, also systematically varies with socioeconomic factors. For example, sectoral composition can directly influence premature deaths through industry-specific risks and accidents. Sector-specific employment may also indirectly affect health. For example, working in shifts, which is much more common in some sectors than in others, has been associated with a significantly higher propensity for coronary heart diseases [CITATION_1] .",
